The Demoable Flow (The "Golden Path")
For a hackathon, you want a "Live Demo" that shows a failure and an autonomous recovery. This proves the "Agentic" nature of the platform.
Step 1: The Trigger (Release Planning)

Action: A user points the platform to a GitHub Repo and a Jira Sprint.
AI Demo: The Planning Agent generates a "Release Readiness Score." It highlights that "Task A is done, but Task B has a circular dependency."
Step 2: The Pre-Flight Check (Validation & Monitoring)

Action: The user clicks "Prepare Deployment."
AI Demo: The Validation Agent scans the last 5 CI runs. It notices a 10% increase in memory usage in the staging logs and flags it: "Warning: Potential memory leak detected in module X."
Step 3: The "Smart" Deployment (Deployment Agent)

Action: Execute a Canary Deployment to Kubernetes.
AI Demo: The Deployment Agent starts shifting 10% of traffic. You show a real-time dashboard of the traffic shift.
Step 4: The Crisis & Recovery (Rollback Agent) — The "Wow" Moment

Action: Manually inject an error into the production environment (e.g., spike 500-level errors).
AI Demo: The Rollback Agent sees the spike, cross-references it with the new deployment logs, and autonomously hits the "Abort" button. It then posts a message in Slack: "Rollback initiated. Error detected in 'Auth-Service'. Reverting to v1.0.2."
Step 5: The Post-Mortem

Action: The Postmortem Agent analyzes the failed logs and the code diff.
AI Demo: It generates a summary: "The failure was caused by an unhandled null pointer in the new login logic. Suggestion: Add a null-check at line 42 of auth.py."